o Sherlock Holmes she is always }{\i\insrsid3304115 the}{\insrsid3304115  woman. I have seldom heard him mention her 
under any other name. In his eyes she eclipses and predominates the whole of her sex. It was not that he felt any emotion akin to love for Irene Adler. All emotions, and that one particularly, were abhorrent to his cold, precise but admirably balanced min
d
. He was, I take it, the most perfect reasoning and observing machine that the world has seen, but as a lover he would have placed himself in a false position. He never spoke of the softer passions, save with a gibe and a sneer. They were admirable things
 for the observer\emdash excellent for drawing the veil from men\rquote 
s motives and actions. But for the trained reasoner to admit such intrusions into his own delicate and finely adjusted temperament was to introduce a distracting factor which might throw a doubt upon
 all his mental results. Grit in a sensitive instrument, or a crack in one of his own high-power lenses, would not be more disturbing than a strong emotion in a nature such as his. And yet there was but one woman to him, and that woman was the late Irene 
Adler, of dubious and questionable memory. 
\par I had seen little of Holmes lately. My marriage had drifted us away from each other. My own complete happiness, and the home-centred interests which rise up around the man who first finds himself master of his own
 establishment, were sufficient to absorb all my attention, while Holmes, who loathed every form of society with his whole Bohemian soul, remained in our lodgings in Baker Street, buried among his old books, and alternating from week to week between cocai
n
e and ambition, the drowsiness of the drug, and the fierce energy of his own keen nature. He was still, as ever, deeply attracted by the study of crime, and occupied his immense faculties and extraordinary powers of observation in following out those clue
s
, and clearing up those mysteries which had been abandoned as hopeless by the official police. From time to time I heard some vague account of his doings: of his summons to Odessa in the case of the Trepoff murder, of his clearing up of the singular trage
d
y of the Atkinson brothers at Trincomalee, and finally of the mission which he had accomplished so delicately and successfully for the reigning family of Holland. Beyond these signs of his activity, however, which I merely shared with all the readers of t
he daily press, I knew little of my former friend and companion. 
\par One night\emdash it was on the twentieth of March, 1888\emdash I was returning from a journey to a patient (for I had now returned to civil practice), when my way led me through Baker Street. As I passed t
he well-remembered door, which must always be associated in my mind with my wooing, and with the dark incidents of the Study in Scarlet, I was seized with a keen desire to see Holmes again, and to know how he was employing his extraordinary powers. His ro
o
ms were brilliantly lit, and, even as I looked up, I saw his tall, spare figure pass twice in a dark silhouette against the blind. He was pacing the room swiftly, eagerly, with his head sunk upon his chest and his hands clasped behind him. To me, who knew
 
his every mood and habit, his attitude and manner told their own story. He was at work again. He had risen out of his drug-created dreams and was hot upon the scent of some new problem. I rang the bell and was shown up to the chamber which had formerly be
en in part my own. 
\par His manner was not effusive. It seldom was; but he was glad, I think, to see me. With hardly a word spoken, but with a kindly eye, he waved me to an armchair, threw across his case of cigars, and indicated a spirit case and a gasogene in
 the corner. Then he stood before the fire and looked me over in his singular introspective fashion. 
\par \'93Wedlock suits you,\'94 he remarked. \'93I think, Watson, that you have put on seven and a half pounds since I saw you.\'94 
\par \'93Seven!\'94 I answered. 
\par \'93Indeed, I should have thought a little more. Just a trifle more, I fancy, Watson. And in practice again, I observe. You did not tell me that you intended to go into harness.\'94 
\par \'93Then, how do you know?\'94 
\par \'93I see it, I deduce it. How do I know that you have been getting yourself very wet lately, and that you have a most clumsy and careless servant girl?\'94 
\par \'93My dear Holmes,\'94 said I, \'93this is too much. You would certainly have been burned, had you lived a few centuries ago. It is true that I had a country walk on Thursday and came home in a dreadful mess, but as I have changed my clothes I can
\rquote t imagine how you deduce it. As to Mary Jane, she is incorrigible, and my wife has given her notice, but there, again, I fail to see how you work it out.\'94 
\par He chuckled to himself and rubbed his long, nervous hands together. 
\par }\pard \s16\qj \fi480\li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3304115 {\insrsid3304115 \'93It is simplicity itself,\'94 said he; \'93
my eyes tell me that on the inside of your left shoe, just where the firelight strikes it, the leather is scored by six almost parallel cuts. Obviously they have been caused by someon
e who has very carelessly scraped round the edges of the sole in order to remove crusted mud from it. Hence, you see, my double deduction that you had been out in vile weather, and that you had a particularly malignant boot-slitting specimen of the London
 
slavey. As to your practice, if a gentleman walks into my rooms smelling of iodoform, with a black mark of nitrate of silver upon his right forefinger, and a bulge on the right side of his top-hat to show where he has secreted his stethoscope, I must be d
ull, indeed, if I do not pronounce him to be an active member of the medical profession.\'94 
\par I could not help laughing at the ease with which he explained his process of deduction. \'93When I hear you give your reasons,\'94 I remarked, \'93the thing always appears to 
me to be so ridiculously simple that I could easily do it myself, though at each successive instance of your reasoning I am baffled until you explain your process. And yet I believe that my eyes are as good as yours.\'94 
\par \'93Quite so,\'94 he answered, lighting a cigarette, and throwing himself down into an armchair. \'93You see, but you do not observe. The distinction is clear. For example, you have frequently seen the steps which lead up from the hall to this room.\'94 

\par \'93Frequently.\'94 
\par \'93How often?\'94 
\par \'93Well, some hundreds of times.\'94 
\par \'93Then how many are there?\'94 
\par \'93How many? I don\rquote t know.\'94 
\par \'93Quite so! You have not observed. And yet you have seen. That is just my point. Now, I know that there are seventeen steps, because I have both seen and observed. By the way, since you are 
interested in these little problems, and since you are good enough to chronicle one or two of my trifling experiences, you may be interested in this.\'94 He threw over a sheet of thick, pink-tinted notepaper which had been lying open upon the table. \'93
It came by the last post,\'94 said he. \'93Read it aloud.\'94 
\par The note was undated, and without either signature or address. 
\par \'93There will call upon you to-night, at a quarter to eight o\rquote clock,\'94 it said, \'93a gentleman who desires to consult you upon a matter of the very dee
pest moment. Your recent services to one of the royal houses of Europe have shown that you are one who may safely be trusted with matters which are of an importance which can hardly be exaggerated. This account of you we have from all quarters received. B
e in your chamber then at that hour, and do not take it amiss if your visitor wear a mask.\'94 
\par \'93This is indeed a mystery,\'94 I remarked. \'93What do you imagine that it means?\'94 
\par \'93I have no data yet. It is a capital mistake to theorise before one has data. Insensibly one begins to twist facts to suit theories, instead of theories to suit facts. But the note itself. What do you deduce from it?\'94 
\par I carefully examined the writing, and the paper upon which it was written. 
\par \'93The man who wrote it was presumably well to do,\'94 I remarked, endeavouring to imitate my companion\rquote s processes. \'93Such paper could not be bought under half a crown a packet. It is peculiarly strong and stiff.\'94 
\par \'93Peculiar\emdash that is the very word,\'94 said Holmes. \'93It is not an English paper at all. Hold it up to the light.\'94 
\par I did so, and saw a large \'93E\'94 with a small \'93g,\'94 a \'93P,\'94 and a large \'93G\'94 with a small \'93t\'94 woven into the texture of the paper. 
\par \'93What do you make of that?\'94 asked Holmes. 
\par \'93The name of the maker, no doubt; or his monogram, rather.\'94 
\par \'93Not at all. The \lquote G\rquote  with the small \lquote t\rquote  stands for \lquote Gesellschaft,\rquote  which is the German for \lquote Company.\rquote  It is a customary contraction like our \lquote Co.\rquote  \lquote P,\rquote 
 of course, stands for \lquote Papier.\rquote  Now for the \lquote Eg.\rquote  Let us glance at our Continental Gazetteer.\'94 He took down a heavy brown volume from his shelves. \'93Eglow, Eglonitz\emdash 
here we are, Egria. It is in a German-speaking country\emdash in Bohemia, not far from Carlsbad. \lquote Remarkable as being the scene of the death of Wallenstein, and for its numerous glass-factories and paper-mills.\rquote  
Ha, ha, my boy, what do you make of that?\'94 His eyes sparkled, and he sent up a great blue triumphant cloud from his cigarette. 
\par \'93The paper was made in Bohemia,\'94 I said. 
\par \'93Precisely. And the man who wrote the note is a German. Do you note the peculiar construction of the sentence\emdash \lquote This account of you we have from all quarters received.\rquote 
 A Frenchman or Russian could not have written that. It is the German who is so uncourteous to his verbs. It only remains, therefore, to discover what is wanted by this German
 who writes upon Bohemian paper and prefers wearing a mask to showing his face. And here he comes, if I am not mistaken, to resolve all our doubts.\'94 
\par As he spoke there was the sharp sound of horses\rquote  hoofs and grating wheels against the curb, followed by a sharp pull at the bell. Holmes whistled. 
\par \'93A pair, by the sound,\'94 said he. \'93Yes,\'94 he continued, glancing out of the window. \'93A nice little brougham and a pair of beauties. A hundred and fifty guineas apiece. There\rquote s money in this case, Watson, if there is nothing else.\'94 

\par \'93I think that I had better go, Holmes.\'94 
\par \'93Not a bit, Doctor. Stay where you are. I am lost without my Boswell. And this promises to be interesting. It would be a pity to miss it.\'94 
\par \'93But your client\emdash \'94 
\par \'93Never mind him. I may want your help, and so may he. Here he comes. Sit down in that armchair, Doctor, and give us your best attention.\'94 
\par A slow and heavy step, which had been heard upon the stairs and in the passage, paused immediately outside the door. Then there was a loud and authoritative tap. 
\par \'93Come in!\'94 said Holmes. 
\par A man entered who could hardly have been less than six feet six inches in height, with the chest and limbs of a Hercules. His dress was rich with a richness which would, in England, be looked upon as akin to bad taste. Heavy
 bands of astrakhan were slashed across the sleeves and fronts of his double-breasted coat, while the deep blue cloak which was thrown over his shoulders was lined with flame-coloured silk and secured at the neck with a brooch which consisted of a single 
f
laming beryl. Boots which extended halfway up his calves, and which were trimmed at the tops with rich brown fur, completed the impression of barbaric opulence which was suggested by his whole appearance. He carried a broad-brimmed hat in his hand, while 
h
e wore across the upper part of his face, extending down past the cheekbones, a black vizard mask, which he had apparently adjusted that very moment, for his hand was still raised to it as he entered. From the lower part of the face he appeared to be a ma
n of strong character, with a thick, hanging lip, and a long, straight chin suggestive of resolution pushed to the length of obstinacy. 
\par \'93You had my note?\'94 he asked with a deep harsh voice and a strongly marked German accent. \'93I told you that I would call.\'94 He looked from one to the other of us, as if uncertain which to address. 
\par \'93Pray take a seat,\'94 said Holmes. \'93This is my friend and colleague, Dr. Watson, who is occasionally good enough to help me in my cases. Whom have I the honour to address?\'94 
\par \'93You may 
address me as the Count Von Kramm, a Bohemian nobleman. I understand that this gentleman, your friend, is a man of honour and discretion, whom I may trust with a matter of the most extreme importance. If not, I should much prefer to communicate with you a
lone.\'94 
\par I rose to go, but Holmes caught me by the wrist and pushed me back into my chair. \'93It is both, or none,\'94 said he. \'93You may say before this gentleman anything which you may say to me.\'94 
\par The Count shrugged his broad shoulders. \'93Then I must begin,\'94 said he, \'93
by binding you both to absolute secrecy for two years; at the end of that time the matter will be of no importance. At present it is not too much to say that it is of such weight it may have an influence upon European history.\'94 
\par \'93I promise,\'94 said Holmes. 
\par \'93And I.\'94 
\par \'93You will excuse this mask,\'94 continued our strange visitor. \'93The august person who employs me wishes his agent to be unknown to you, and I may confess at once that the title by which I have just called myself is not exactly my own.\'94 
\par \'93I was aware of it,\'94 said Holmes dryly. 
\par \'93The circumstances are of great delicacy, and every precaution has to be taken to quench what might grow to be an immense scandal and seriously compromise one of the reigning families of Europe. To speak plainly, the mat
ter implicates the great House of Ormstein, hereditary kings of Bohemia.\'94 
\par \'93I was also aware of that,\'94 murmured Holmes, settling himself down in his armchair and closing his eyes. 
\par Our visitor glanced with some apparent surprise at the languid, lounging fi
gure of the man who had been no doubt depicted to him as the most incisive reasoner and most energetic agent in Europe. Holmes slowly reopened his eyes and looked impatiently at his gigantic client. 
\par \'93If your Majesty would condescend to state your case,\'94 he remarked, \'93I should be better able to advise you.\'94 
\par The man sprang from his chair and paced up and down the room in uncontrollable agitation. Then, with a gesture of desperation, he tore the mask from his face and hurled it upon the ground. \'93You are right,\'94 he cried; \'93
I am the King. Why should I attempt to conceal it?\'94 
\par \'93Why, indeed?\'94 murmured Holmes. \'93Your Majesty had not spoken before I was aware that I was addressing Wilhelm Gottsreich Sigismond von Ormstein, Grand Duke of Cassel-Felstein, and hereditary King of Bohemia.\'94 
\par \'93But you can understand,\'94 said our strange visitor, sitting down once more and passing his hand over his high white forehead, \'93you can understand that I am not accustomed to doing such business in my own person. Yet the matter was so 
delicate that I could not confide it to an agent without putting myself in his power. I have come }{\i\insrsid3304115 incognito}{\insrsid3304115  from Prague for the purpose of consulting you.\'94 
\par \'93Then, pray consult,\'94 said Holmes, shutting his eyes once more. 
\par \'93The facts are briefly these: Some five years ago, during a lengthy visit to Warsaw, I made the acquaintance of the well-known adventuress, Irene Adler. The name is no doubt familiar to you.\'94 
\par \'93Kindly look her up in my index, Doctor,\'94 murmured Holmes without opening his eyes. For many year
s he had adopted a system of docketing all paragraphs concerning men and things, so that it was difficult to name a subject or a person on which he could not at once furnish information. In this case I found her biography sandwiched in between that of a H
ebrew rabbi and that of a staff-commander who had written a monograph upon the deep-sea fishes. 
\par \'93Let me see!\'94 said Holmes. \'93Hum! Born in New Jersey in the year 1858. Contralto\emdash hum! La Scala, hum! Prima donna Imperial Opera of Warsaw\emdash yes! Retired from operatic stage\emdash ha! Living in London\emdash 
quite so! Your Majesty, as I understand, became entangled with this young person, wrote her some compromising letters, and is now desirous of getting those letters back.\'94 
\par \'93Precisely so. But how\emdash \'94 
\par \'93Was there a secret marriage?\'94 
\par \'93None.\'94 
\par \'93No legal papers or certificates?\'94 
\par \'93None.\'94 
\par \'93Then I fail to follow your Majesty. If this young person should produce her letters for blackmailing or other purposes, how is she to prove their authenticity?\'94 
\par \'93There is the writing.\'94 
\par \'93Pooh, pooh! Forgery.\'94 
\par \'93My private note-paper.\'94 
\par \'93Stolen.\'94 
\par \'93My own seal.\'94 
\par \'93Imitated.\'94 
\par \'93My photograph.\'94 
\par \'93Bought.\'94 
\par \'93We were both in the photograph.\'94 
\par \'93Oh, dear! That is very bad! Your Majesty has indeed committed an indiscretion.\'94 
\par \'93I was mad\emdash insane.\'94 
\par \'93You have compromised yourself seriously.\'94 
\par \'93I was only Crown Prince then. I was young. I am but thirty now.\'94 
\par \'93It must be recovered.\'94 
\par \'93We have tried and failed.\'94 
\par \'93Your Majesty must pay. It must be bought.\'94 
\par \'93She will not sell.\'94 
\par \'93Stolen, then.\'94 
\par \'93Five attempts have been made. Twice burglars in my pay ransacked her house. Once we diverted her luggage when she travelled. Twice she has been waylaid. There has been no result.\'94 
\par \'93No sign of it?\'94 
\par \'93Absolutely none.\'94 
\par Holmes laughed. \'93It is quite a pretty little problem,\'94 said he. 
\par \'93But a very serious one to me,\'94 returned the King reproachfully. 
\par \'93Very, indeed. And what does she propose to do with the photograph?\'94 
\par \'93To ruin me.\'94 
\par \'93But how?\'94 
\par \'93I am about to be married.\'94 
\par \'93So I have heard.\'94 
\par \'93To Clotilde Lothman von Saxe-Meningen, second daughter of the King of Scandinavia. You may know the strict principles of her family. She is herself the very soul of delicacy. A shadow of a doubt as to my conduct would bring the matter to an end.\'94 

\par \'93And Irene Adler?\'94 
\par \'93Threatens to sen
d them the photograph. And she will do it. I know that she will do it. You do not know her, but she has a soul of steel. She has the face of the most beautiful of women, and the mind of the most resolute of men. Rather than I should marry another woman, t
here are no lengths to which she would not go\emdash none.\'94 
\par \'93You are sure that she has not sent it yet?\'94 
\par \'93I am sure.\'94 
\par \'93And why?\'94 
\par \'93Because she has said that she would send it on the day when the betrothal was publicly proclaimed. That will be next Monday.\'94 
\par \'93Oh, then we have three days yet,\'94 said Holmes with a yawn. \'93That is very fortunate, as I have one or two matters of importance to look into just at present. Your Majesty will, of course, stay in London for the present?\'94 
\par \'93Certainly. You will find me at the Langham under the name of the Count Von Kramm.\'94 
\par \'93Then I shall drop you a line to let you know how we progress.\'94 
\par \'93Pray do so. I shall be all anxiety.\'94 
\par \'93Then, as to money?\'94 
\par \'93You have }{\i\insrsid3304115 carte blanche}{\insrsid3304115 .\'94 
\par \'93Absolutely?\'94 
\par \'93I tell you that I would give one of the provinces of my kingdom to have that photograph.\'94 
\par \'93And for present expenses?\'94 
\par The King took a heavy chamois leather bag from under his cloak and laid it on the table. 
\par \'93There are three hundred pounds in gold and seven hundred in notes,\'94 he said. 
\par Holmes scribbled a receipt upon a sheet of his note-book and handed it to him. 
\par \'93And Mademoiselle\rquote s address?\'94 he asked. 
\par \'93Is Briony Lodge, Serpentine Avenue, St. John\rquote s Wood.\'94 
\par Holmes took a note of it. \'93One other question,\'94 said he. \'93Was the photograph a cabinet?\'94 
\par \'93It was.\'94 
