t do it. I know it, and I want you to start upon your work knowing it, too. Never let yourself doubt upon that point. We have known each other since we were little children, and I know his fa
ults as no one else does; but he is too tender-hearted to hurt a fly. Such a charge is absurd to anyone who really knows him.\'94 
\par \'93I hope we may clear him, Miss Turner,\'94 said Sherlock Holmes. \'93You may rely upon my doing all that I can.\'94 
\par \'93But you have read the evidence. You have formed some conclusion? Do you not see some loophole, some flaw? Do you not yourself think that he is innocent?\'94 
\par \'93I think that it is very probable.\'94 
\par \'93There, now!\'94 she cried, throwing back her head and looking defiantly at Lestrade. \'93You hear! He gives me hopes.\'94 
