\par There was no rain, as Holmes had foretold, and the morning broke bright and cloudless. At nine o\rquote clock Lestrade called for us with the carriage, and we set off for Hatherley Farm and the Boscombe Pool. 
\par \'93There is serious news this morning,\'94 Lestrade observed. \'93It is said that Mr. Turner, of the Hall, is so ill that his life is despaired of.\'94 
\par \'93An elderly man, I presume?\'94 said Holmes. 
\par \'93About sixty; but his constitution has been shattered by his life abroad, and he has been in failing health for some time. This business has had a very bad effect upon him. He was an old friend of McCarthy\rquote 
s, and, I may add, a great benefactor to him, for I have learned that he gave him Hatherley Farm rent free.\'94 
\par \'93Indeed! That is interesting,\'94 said Holmes. 
\par \'93Oh, yes! In a hundred other ways he has helped him. Everybody about here speaks of his kindness to him.\'94 
\par \'93Really! Does it not strike you as a little singular that this McCarthy, who appears to have had little of his own, and to have been under such obligations to Turner, should still talk of marrying his son to Turner\rquote 
s daughter, who is, presumably, heiress to the estate, and that in such a ve
ry cocksure manner, as if it were merely a case of a proposal and all else would follow? It is the more strange, since we know that Turner himself was averse to the idea. The daughter told us as much. Do you not deduce something from that?\'94 
\par \'93We have got to the deductions and the inferences,\'94 said Lestrade, winking at me. \'93I find it hard enough to tackle facts, Holmes, without flying away after theories and fancies.\'94 
\par \'93You are right,\'94 said Holmes demurely; \'93you do find it very hard to tackle the facts.\'94 
\par \'93Anyhow, I have grasped one fact which you seem to find it difficult to get hold of,\'94 replied Lestrade with some warmth. 
\par \'93And that is\emdash \'94 
\par \'93That McCarthy senior met his death from McCarthy junior and that all theories to the contrary are the merest moonshine.\'94 
\par \'93Well, moonshine is a brighter thing than fog,\'94 said Holmes, laughing. \'93But I am very much mistaken if this is not Hatherley Farm upon the left.\'94 
\par \'93Yes, that is it.\'94 It was a widespread, comfortable-looking building, two-storied, slate-roofed, with grea
t yellow blotches of lichen upon the grey walls. The drawn blinds and the smokeless chimneys, however, gave it a stricken look, as though the weight of this horror still lay heavy upon it. We called at the door, when the maid, at Holmes\rquote 
