aced his way to the farther side of this and lay down once more upon his face with a little cry of satisfaction. For a long time he remained there, turning over the leaves and dried sticks, gathering up what seemed to me to be dust into an envelope and ex
a
mining with his lens not only the ground but even the bark of the tree as far as he could reach. A jagged stone was lying among the moss, and this also he carefully examined and retained. Then he followed a pathway through the wood until he came to the hi
ghroad, where all traces were lost. 
\par \'93It has been a case of considerable interest,\'94 he remarked, returning to his natural manner. \'93I fancy that this grey house on the right must be the lodge. I think that I will go in and have a word with Moran, and perhaps
