 THE ADVENTURE OF THE BLUE CARBUNCLE{\*\bkmkend 7}
\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj \fi480\li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3304115 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid3304115 \line }{\fs36\insrsid3304115 I}{\insrsid3304115 
 had called upon my friend Sherlock Holmes upon the second morning after Christmas, with the intenti
on of wishing him the compliments of the season. He was lounging upon the sofa in a purple dressing-gown, a pipe-rack within his reach upon the right, and a pile of crumpled morning papers, evidently newly studied, near at hand. Beside the couch was a woo
d
en chair, and on the angle of the back hung a very seedy and disreputable hard-felt hat, much the worse for wear, and cracked in several places. A lens and a forceps lying upon the seat of the chair suggested that the hat had been suspended in this manner
 for the purpose of examination. 
\par \'93You are engaged,\'94 said I; \'93perhaps I interrupt you.\'94 
\par \'93Not at all. I am glad to have a friend with whom I can discuss my results. The matter is a perfectly trivial one\'94\emdash he jerked his thumb in the direction of the old hat\emdash \'93
but there are points in connection with it which are not entirely devoid of interest and even of instruction.\'94 
\par }\pard \s16\qj \fi480\li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid3304115 {\insrsid3304115 
I seated myself in his armchair and warmed my hands before his crackling fire, for a sharp frost had set in, and the windows were thick with the ice crystals. \'93I suppose,\'94 I remarked, \'93
that, homely as it looks, this thing has some deadly story linked on to it\emdash that it is the clue which will guide you in the solution of some mystery and the punishment of some crime.\'94 
\par \'93No, no. No crime,\'94 said Sherlock Holmes, laughing. \'93
Only one of those whimsical little incidents which will happen when you have four million human beings all jostling each other within the space of a few square miles. Amid the action and reaction of so dense a swarm of humanity, every
 possible combination of events may be expected to take place, and many a little problem will be presented which may be striking and bizarre without being criminal. We have already had experience of such.\'94 
\par \'93So much so,\'94 I remarked, \'93that of the last six cases which I have added to my notes, three have been entirely free of any legal crime.\'94 
\par \'93Precisely. You allude to my attempt to recover the Irene Adler papers, to the singular case of Miss Mary Sutherland, and to the adventure of the man with the twisted 
lip. Well, I have no doubt that this small matter will fall into the same innocent category. You know Peterson, the commissionaire?\'94 
\par \'93Yes.\'94 
\par \'93It is to him that this trophy belongs.\'94 
\par \'93It is his hat.\'94 
\par \'93No, no, he found it. Its owner is unknown. I beg that
 you will look upon it not as a battered billycock but as an intellectual problem. And, first, as to how it came here. It arrived upon Christmas morning, in company with a good fat goose, which is, I have no doubt, roasting at this moment in front of Pete
rson\rquote s fire. The facts are these: about four o\rquote 
clock on Christmas morning, Peterson, who, as you know, is a very honest fellow, was returning from some small jollification and was making his way homeward down Tottenham Court Road. In front of him he saw, in
 the gaslight, a tallish man, walking with a slight stagger, and carrying a white goose slung over his shoulder. As he reached the corner of Goodge Street, a row broke out between this stranger and a little knot of roughs. One of the latter knocked off th
e man\rquote 
s hat, on which he raised his stick to defend himself and, swinging it over his head, smashed the shop window behind him. Peterson had rushed forward to protect the stranger from his assailants; but the man, shocked at having broken the window, and se
eing an official-looking person in uniform rushing towards him, dropped his goose, took to his heels, and vanished amid the labyrinth of small streets which lie at the back of Tottenham Court Road. The roughs had also fled at the appearance of Peterson, s
o that he was left in possession of the field of battle, and also of the spoils of victory in the shape of this battered hat and a most unimpeachable Christmas goose.\'94 
\par \'93Which surely he restored to their owner?\'94 
\par \'93My dear fellow, there lies the problem. It is true that \lquote For Mrs. Henry Baker\rquote  was printed upon a small card which was tied to the bird\rquote s left leg, and it is also true that the initials \lquote H. B.\rquote 
 are legible upon the lining of this hat, but as there are some thousands of Bakers, and some hundreds of Henry Bakers in this city of ours, it is not easy to restore lost property to any one of them.\'94 
\par \'93What, then, did Peterson do?\'94 
\par \'93He brought round both hat and goose to me on Christmas morning, knowing that even the smallest problems are of interest to me.
 The goose we retained until this morning, when there were signs that, in spite of the slight frost, it would be well that it should be eaten without unnecessary delay. Its finder has carried it off, therefore, to fulfil the ultimate destiny of a goose, w
hile I continue to retain the hat of the unknown gentleman who lost his Christmas dinner.\'94 
\par \'93Did he not advertise?\'94 
\par \'93No.\'94 
\par \'93Then, what clue could you have as to his identity?\'94 
\par \'93Only as much as we can deduce.\'94 
\par \'93From his hat?\'94 
\par \'93Precisely.\'94 
\par \'93But you are joking. What can you gather from this old battered felt?\'94 
\par \'93Here is my lens. You know my methods. What can you gather yourself as to the individuality of the man who has worn this article?\'94 
\par I took the tattered object in my hands and turned it over rather ruefully. It was a very ordinary black hat of the usual round shape, hard and much the worse for wear. The lining had been of red silk, but was a good deal discoloured. There was no maker
\rquote s name; but, as Holmes had remarked, the initials \'93H. B.\'94 were scrawl
ed upon one side. It was pierced in the brim for a hat-securer, but the elastic was missing. For the rest, it was cracked, exceedingly dusty, and spotted in several places, although there seemed to have been some attempt to hide the discoloured patches by
 smearing them with ink. 
\par \'93I can see nothing,\'94 said I, handing it back to my friend. 
\par \'93On the contrary, Watson, you can see everything. You fail, however, to reason from what you see. You are too timid in drawing your inferences.\'94 
\par \'93Then, pray tell me what it is that you can infer from this hat?\'94 
\par He picked it up and gazed at it in the peculiar introspective fashion which was characteristic of him. \'93It is perhaps less suggestive than it might have been,\'94 he remarked, \'93and yet there are a few inferences which
 are very distinct, and a few others which represent at least a strong balance of probability. That the man was highly intellectual is of course obvious upon the face of it, and also that he was fairly well-to-do within the last three years, although he h
a
s now fallen upon evil days. He had foresight, but has less now than formerly, pointing to a moral retrogression, which, when taken with the decline of his fortunes, seems to indicate some evil influence, probably drink, at work upon him. This may account
 also for the obvious fact that his wife has ceased to love him.\'94 
\par \'93My dear Holmes!\'94 
\par \'93He has, however, retained some degree of self-respect,\'94 he continued, disregarding my remonstrance. \'93He is a man who leads a sedentary life, goes out little, is out of tr
aining entirely, is middle-aged, has grizzled hair which he has had cut within the last few days, and which he anoints with lime-cream. These are the more patent facts which are to be deduced from his hat. Also, by the way, that it is extremely improbable
 that he has gas laid on in his house.\'94 
\par \'93You are certainly joking, Holmes.\'94 
\par \'93Not in the least. Is it possible that even now, when I give you these results, you are unable to see how they are attained?\'94 
\par \'93I have no doubt that I am very stupid, but I must confess that I am unable to follow you. For example, how did you deduce that this man was intellectual?\'94 
\par For answer Holmes clapped the hat upon his head. It came right over the forehead and settled upon the bridge of his nose. \'93It is a question of cubic capacity,\'94 said he; \'93a man with so large a brain must have something in it.\'94 
\par \'93The decline of his fortunes, then?\'94 
\par \'93This hat is three years old. These flat brims curled at the edge came in then. It is a hat of the very best quality. Look at the band of ribb
ed silk and the excellent lining. If this man could afford to buy so expensive a hat three years ago, and has had no hat since, then he has assuredly gone down in the world.\'94 
\par \'93Well, that is clear enough, certainly. But how about the foresight and the moral retrogression?\'94 
\par Sherlock Holmes laughed. \'93Here is the foresight,\'94 said he putting his finger upon the little disc and loop of the hat-securer. \'93They are never sold upon hats. If this man ordered one, it is a sign of a certain amount of foresight, since 
he went out of his way to take this precaution against the wind. But since we see that he has broken the elastic and has not troubled to replace it, it is obvious that he has less foresight now than formerly, which is a distinct proof of a weakening natur
e. On the other hand, he has endeavoured to conceal some of these stains upon the felt by daubing them with ink, which is a sign that he has not entirely lost his self-respect.\'94 
\par \'93Your reasoning is certainly plausible.\'94 
\par \'93The further points, that he is midd
le-aged, that his hair is grizzled, that it has been recently cut, and that he uses lime-cream, are all to be gathered from a close examination of the lower part of the lining. The lens discloses a large number of hair-ends, clean cut by the scissors of t
h
e barber. They all appear to be adhesive, and there is a distinct odour of lime-cream. This dust, you will observe, is not the gritty, grey dust of the street but the fluffy brown dust of the house, showing that it has been hung up indoors most of the tim
e, while the marks of moisture upon the inside are proof positive that the wearer perspired very freely, and could therefore, hardly be in the best of training.\'94 
\par \'93But his wife\emdash you said that she had ceased to love him.\'94 
\par \'93This hat has not been brushed for weeks. When I see you, my dear Watson, with a week\rquote 
s accumulation of dust upon your hat, and when your wife allows you to go out in such a state, I shall fear that you also have been unfortunate enough to lose your wife\rquote s affection.\'94 
\par \'93But he might be a bachelor.\'94 
\par \'93Nay, he was bringing home the goose as a peace-offering to his wife. Remember the card upon the bird\rquote s leg.\'94 
\par \'93You have an answer to everything. But how on earth do you deduce that the gas is not laid on in his house?\'94 
\par \'93One tallow stain, or even two, might come by chance; but when I see no less than five, I think that there can be little doubt that the individual must be brought into frequent contact with burning tallow\emdash 
walks upstairs at night probably with his hat in one hand and a guttering candle in the other. Anyhow, he never got tallow-stains from a gas-jet. Are you satisfied?\'94 
\par \'93Well, it is very ingenious,\'94 said I, laughing; \'93but since, as you said just now, there has been no crime committed, and no harm done save the loss of a goose, all this seems to be rather a waste of energy.\'94 
\par Sherlock Holmes had opened his mouth to reply, when the door flew open, and Peterson, the commissionaire, rushed into the apartment with flushed cheeks and the face of a man who is dazed with astonishment. 
\par \'93The goose, Mr. Holmes! The goose, sir!\'94 he gasped. 
\par \'93Eh? What of it, then? Has it returned to life and flapped off through the kitchen window?\'94 Holmes twisted himself round upon the sofa to get a fairer view of the man\rquote s excited face. 
\par \'93See here, sir! See what my wife found in its crop!\'94
 He held out his hand and displayed upon the centre of the palm a brilliantly scintillating blue stone, rather smaller than a bean in size, but of such purity and radiance that it twinkled like an electric point in the dark hollow of his hand. 
\par Sherlock Holmes sat up with a whistle. \'93By Jove, Peterson!\'94 said he, \'93this is treasure trove indeed. I suppose you know what you have got?\'94 
\par \'93A diamond, sir? A precious stone. It cuts into glass as though it were putty.\'94 
\par \'93It\rquote s more than a precious stone. It is }{\i\insrsid3304115 the}{\insrsid3304115  precious stone.\'94 
\par \'93Not the Countess of Morcar\rquote s blue carbuncle!\'94 I ejaculated. 
\par \'93Precisely so. I ought to know its size and shape, seeing that I have read the advertisement about it in }{\i\insrsid3304115 The Times}{\insrsid3304115  every day lately. It is absolutely 
unique, and its value can only be conjectured, but the reward offered of }{\i\insrsid3304115 \'a3}{\insrsid3304115 1000 is certainly not within a twentieth part of the market price.\'94 
\par \'93A thousand pounds! Great Lord of mercy!\'94 The commissionaire plumped down into a chair and stared from one to the other of us. 
\par \'93That is the reward, and I have reason to know that there are sentimental considerations in the background which would induce the Countess to part with half her fortune if she could but recover the gem.\'94 
\par \'93It was lost, if I remember aright, at the Hotel Cosmopolitan,\'94 I remarked. 
\par \'93Precisely so, on December 22nd, just five days ago. John Horner, a plumber, was accused of having abstracted it from the lady\rquote s jewel-case. The evidence against him was so strong that the case has been referred to 
the Assizes. I have some account of the matter here, I believe.\'94 He rummaged amid his newspapers, glancing over the dates, until at last he smoothed one out, doubled it over, and read the following paragraph: 
\par \'93Hotel Cosmopolitan Jewel Robbery. John Horner
, 26, plumber, was brought up upon the charge of having upon the 22nd inst., abstracted from the jewel-case of the Countess of Morcar the valuable gem known as the blue carbuncle. James Ryder, upper-attendant at the hotel, gave his evidence to the effect 
t
hat he had shown Horner up to the dressing-room of the Countess of Morcar upon the day of the robbery in order that he might solder the second bar of the grate, which was loose. He had remained with Horner some little time, but had finally been called awa
y
. On returning, he found that Horner had disappeared, that the bureau had been forced open, and that the small morocco casket in which, as it afterwards transpired, the Countess was accustomed to keep her jewel, was lying empty upon the dressing-table. Ry
der instantly gave the alarm, and Horner was arrested the same evening; but the stone could not be found either upon his person or in his rooms. Catherine Cusack, maid to the Countess, deposed to having heard Ryder\rquote 
s cry of dismay on discovering the robbery
, and to having rushed into the room, where she found matters as described by the last witness. Inspector Bradstreet, B division, gave evidence as to the arrest of Horner, who struggled frantically, and protested his innocence in the strongest terms. Evid
e
nce of a previous conviction for robbery having been given against the prisoner, the magistrate refused to deal summarily with the offence, but referred it to the Assizes. Horner, who had shown signs of intense emotion during the proceedings, fainted away
 at the conclusion and was carried out of court.\'94 
\par \'93Hum! So much for the police-court,\'94 said Holmes thoughtfully, tossing aside the paper. \'93The question for us now to solve is the sequence of events leading from a rifled jewel-case at one end to the crop of
 a goose in Tottenham Court Road at the other. You see, Watson, our little deductions have suddenly assumed a much more important and less innocent aspect. Here is the stone; the stone came from the goose, and the goose came from Mr. Henry Baker, the gent
l
eman with the bad hat and all the other characteristics with which I have bored you. So now we must set ourselves very seriously to finding this gentleman and ascertaining what part he has played in this little mystery. To do this, we must try the simples
t means first, and these lie undoubtedly in an advertisement in all the evening papers. If this fail, I shall have recourse to other methods.\'94 
\par \'93What will you say?\'94 
\par \'93Give me a pencil and that slip of paper. Now, then: \lquote Found at the corner of Goodge Street, a goose and a black felt hat. Mr. Henry Baker can have the same by applying at 6:30 this evening at 221B, Baker Street.\rquote 
 That is clear and concise.\'94 
\par \'93Very. But will he see it?\'94 
\par \'93Well, he is sure to keep an eye on the papers, since, to a poor man, the lo
ss was a heavy one. He was clearly so scared by his mischance in breaking the window and by the approach of Peterson that he thought of nothing but flight, but since then he must have bitterly regretted the impulse which caused him to drop his bird. Then,
 again, the introduction of his name will cause him to see it, for everyone who knows him will direct his attention to it. Here you are, Peterson, run down to the advertising agency and have this put in the evening papers.\'94 
\par \'93In which, sir?\'94 
\par \'93Oh, in the }{\i\insrsid3304115 Globe}{\insrsid3304115 , }{\i\insrsid3304115 Star}{\insrsid3304115 , }{\i\insrsid3304115 Pall Mall}{\insrsid3304115 , }{\i\insrsid3304115 St. James\rquote s}{\insrsid3304115 , }{\i\insrsid3304115 Evening News}{
\insrsid3304115 , }{\i\insrsid3304115 Standard}{\insrsid3304115 , }{\i\insrsid3304115 Echo}{\insrsid3304115 , and any others that occur to you.\'94 
\par \'93Very well, sir. And this stone?\'94 
\par \'93Ah, yes, I shall keep the stone. Thank you. And, I say, Peterson, just buy a goose on your way back and leave it here with me, for we must have one to give to this gentleman in place of the one which your family is now devouring.\'94 
\par When the commissionaire had gone, Holmes took up the stone and held it against the light. \'93It\rquote s a bonny thing,\'94 said he. \'93Just see how it glint
s and sparkles. Of course it is a nucleus and focus of crime. Every good stone is. They are the devil\rquote 
s pet baits. In the larger and older jewels every facet may stand for a bloody deed. This stone is not yet twenty years old. It was found in the banks of 
the Amoy River in southern China and is remarkable in having every characteristic of the carbuncle, save that it is blue in shade instead of ruby red. In spite of its youth, it has already a sinister history. There have been two murders, a vitriol-throwin
g, a suicide, and several robberies brought about for the sake of this forty-grain weight of crystallised charcoal. Who would think that so pretty a toy would be a purveyor to the gallows and the prison? I\rquote 
ll lock it up in my strong box now and drop a line to the Countess to say that we have it.\'94 
\par \'93Do you think that this man Horner is innocent?\'94 
\par \'93I cannot tell.\'94 
\par \'93Well, then, do you imagine that this other one, Henry Baker, had anything to do with the matter?\'94 
\par \'93It is, I think, much more likely that Henry B
aker is an absolutely innocent man, who had no idea that the bird which he was carrying was of considerably more value than if it were made of solid gold. That, however, I shall determine by a very simple test if we have an answer to our advertisement.
\'94 
\par \'93And you can do nothing until then?\'94 
\par \'93Nothing.\'94 
\par \'93In that case I shall continue my professional round. But I shall come back in the evening at the hour you have mentioned, for I should like to see the solution of so tangled a business.\'94 
\par \'93Very glad to see you. I dine at seven. There is a woodcock, I believe. By the way, in view of recent occurrences, perhaps I ought to ask Mrs. Hudson to examine its crop.\'94 
\par I had been delayed at a case, and it was a little after half-past six when I found myself in Baker St
reet once more. As I approached the house I saw a tall man in a Scotch bonnet with a coat which was buttoned up to his chin waiting outside in the bright semicircle which was thrown from the fanlight. Just as I arrived the door was opened, and we were sho
wn up together to Holmes\rquote  room. 
\par \'93Mr. Henry Baker, I believe,\'94 said he, rising from his armchair and greeting his visitor with the easy air of geniality which he could so readily assume. \'93Pray take this chair by the fire, Mr. Baker. It is a cold night, and 
I observe that your circulation is more adapted for summer than for winter. Ah, Watson, you have just come at the right time. Is that your hat, Mr. Baker?\'94 
\par \'93Yes, sir, that is undoubtedly my hat.\'94 
\par He was a large man with rounded shoulders, a massive head, and a broad, intelligent face, sloping down to a pointed beard of grizzled brown. A touch of red in nose and cheeks, with a slight tremor of his extended hand, recalled Holmes\rquote 
 surmise as to his habits. His rusty black frock-coat was buttoned right up in 
front, with the collar turned up, and his lank wrists protruded from his sleeves without a sign of cuff or shirt. He spoke in a slow staccato fashion, choosing his words with care, and gave the impression generally of a man of learning and letters who had
 had ill-usage at the hands of fortune. 
\par \'93We have retained these things for some days,\'94 said Holmes, \'93because we expected to see an advertisement from you giving your address. I am at a loss to know now why you did not advertise.\'94 
\par Our visitor gave a rather shamefaced laugh. \'93Shillings have not been so plentiful with me as they once were,\'94 he remarked. \'93
I had no doubt that the gang of roughs who assaulted me had carried off both my hat and the bird. I did not care to spend more money in a hopeless attempt at recovering them.\'94 
\par \'93Very naturally. By the way, about the bird, we were compelled to eat it.\'94 
\par \'93To eat it!\'94 Our visitor half rose from his chair in his excitement. 
\par \'93Yes, it would have been of no use to anyone had we not done so. But I presume that this other goose upon the sideboard, which is about the same weight and perfectly fresh, will answer your purpose equally well?\'94 
\par \'93Oh, certainly, certainly,\'94 answered Mr. Baker with a sigh of relief. 
\par \'93Of course, we still have the feathers, legs, crop, and so on of your own bird, so if you wish\emdash \'94 
\par The man burst into a hearty laugh. \'93They might be useful to me as relics of my adventure,\'94 said he, \'93but beyond that I can hardly see what use the }{\i\insrsid3304115 disjecta membra}{\insrsid3304115 
 of my late acquaintance are going to be to me. No, sir, I think that, with your permission, I will confine my attentions to the excellent bird which I perceive upon the sideboard.\'94 
\par Sherlock Holmes glanced sharply across at me with a slight shrug of his shoulders. 
\par \'93There is your hat, then, and there your bird,\'94 said he. \'93By the way, would it bore you to tell me where you got the other one from? I am somewhat of a fowl fancier, and I have seldom seen a better grown goose.\'94 
\par \'93Certainly, sir,\'94 said Baker, who had risen and tucked his newly gained property under his arm. \'93There are a few of us who frequent the Alpha Inn, near the Museum\emdash 
we are to be found in the Museum itself during the day, you understand. This year our good host, Windigate by name, instituted a goose club, by which, on consideration of some few pe
nce every week, we were each to receive a bird at Christmas. My pence were duly paid, and the rest is familiar to you. I am much indebted to you, sir, for a Scotch bonnet is fitted neither to my years nor my gravity.\'94
 With a comical pomposity of manner he bowed solemnly to both of us and strode off upon his way. 
\par \'93So much for Mr. Henry Baker,\'94 said Holmes when he had closed the door behind him. \'93It is quite certain that he knows nothing whatever about the matter. Are you hungry, Watson?\'94 
\par \'93Not particularly.\'94 
\par \'93Then I suggest that we turn our dinner into a supper and follow up this clue while it is still hot.\'94 
\par \'93By all means.\'94 
\par It was a bitter night, so we drew on our ulsters and wrapped cravats about our throats. Outside, the stars were shining coldly in a c
loudless sky, and the breath of the passers-by blew out into smoke like so many pistol shots. Our footfalls rang out crisply and loudly as we swung through the doctors\rquote 
 quarter, Wimpole Street, Harley Street, and so through Wigmore Street into Oxford Stree
t. In a quarter of an hour we were in Bloomsbury at the Alpha Inn, which is a small public-house at the corner of one of the streets which runs down into Holborn. Holmes pushed open the door of the private bar and ordered two glasses of beer from the rudd
y-faced, white-aproned landlord. 
\par \'93Your beer should be excellent if it is as good as your geese,\'94 said he. 
\par \'93My geese!\'94 The man seemed surprised. 
\par \'93Yes. I was speaking only half an hour ago to Mr. Henry Baker, who was a member of your goose club.\'94 
\par \'93Ah! yes, I see. But you see, sir, them\rquote s not }{\i\insrsid3304115 our}{\insrsid3304115  geese.\'94 
\par \'93Indeed! Whose, then?\'94 
\par \'93Well, I got the two dozen from a salesman in Covent Garden.\'94 
\par \'93Indeed? I know some of them. Which was it?\'94 
\par \'93Breckinridge is his name.\'94 
\par \'93Ah! I don\rquote t know him. Well, here\rquote s your good health landlord, and prosperity to your house. Good-night.\'94 
\par \'93Now for Mr. Breckinridge,\'94 he continued, buttoning up his coat as we came out into the frosty air. \'93Remember, Watson that though we have so homely a thing as a goose at one end of this chain,
 we have at the other a man who will certainly get seven years\rquote 
 penal servitude unless we can establish his innocence. It is possible that our inquiry may but confirm his guilt; but, in any case, we have a line of investigation which has been missed by the
 police, and which a singular chance has placed in our hands. Let us follow it out to the bitter end. Faces to the south, then, and quick march!\'94 
\par We passed across Holborn, down Endell Street, and so through a zigzag of slums to Covent Garden Market. One o
f the largest stalls bore the name of Breckinridge upon it, and the proprietor a horsey-looking man, with a sharp face and trim side-whiskers was helping a boy to put up the shutters. 
\par \'93Good-evening. It\rquote s a cold night,\'94 said Holmes. 
\par The salesman nodded and shot a questioning glance at my companion. 
\par \'93Sold out of geese, I see,\'94 continued Holmes, pointing at the bare slabs of marble. 
\par \'93Let you have five hundred to-morrow morning.\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s no good.\'94 
\par \'93Well, there are some on the stall with the gas-flare.\'94 
\par \'93Ah, but I was recommended to you.\'94 
\par \'93Who by?\'94 
\par \'93The landlord of the Alpha.\'94 
\par \'93Oh, yes; I sent him a couple of dozen.\'94 
\par \'93Fine birds they were, too. Now where did you get them from?\'94 
\par To my surprise the question provoked a burst of anger from the salesman. 
\par \'93Now, then, mister,\'94 said he, with his head cocked and his arms akimbo, \'93what are you driving at? Let\rquote s have it straight, now.\'94 
\par \'93It is straight enough. I should like to know who sold you the geese which you supplied to the Alpha.\'94 
\par \'93Well then, I shan\rquote t tell you. So now!\'94 
\par \'93Oh, it is a matter of no importance; but I don\rquote t know why you should be so warm over such a trifle.\'94 
\par \'93Warm! You\rquote d be as warm, maybe, if you were as pestered as I am. When I pay good money for a good article there should be an end of the business; but it\rquote s \lquote Where are the geese?\rquote  and \lquote Who did you sell the geese to?
\rquote  and \lquote What will you take for the geese?\rquote  One would think they were the only geese in the world, to hear the fuss that is made over them.\'94 
\par \'93Well, I have no connection with any other people who have been making inquiries,\'94 said Holmes carelessly. \'93If you won\rquote t tell us the bet is off, that is all. But I\rquote 
m always ready to back my opinion on a matter of fowls, and I have a fiver on it that the bird I ate is country bred.\'94 
\par \'93Well, then, you\rquote ve lost your fiver, for it\rquote s town bred,\'94 snapped the salesman. 
\par \'93It\rquote s nothing of the kind.\'94 
\par \'93I say it is.\'94 
\par \'93I don\rquote t believe it.\'94 
\par \'93D\rquote you think you know more about fowls than I, who have handled them ever since I was a nipper? I tell you, all those birds that went to the Alpha were town bred.\'94 
\par \'93You\rquote ll never persuade me to believe that.\'94 
\par \'93Will you bet, then?\'94 
\par \'93It\rquote s merely taking your money, for I know that I am right. But I\rquote ll have a sovereign on with you, just to teach you not to be obstinate.\'94 
\par The salesman chuckled grimly. \'93Bring me the books, Bill,\'94 said he. 
\par The small boy brought round a small thin volume and a great greasy-backed one, laying them out together beneath the hanging lamp. 
\par \'93Now then, Mr. Cocksure,\'94 said the salesman, \'93I thought that I was out of geese, but before I finish you\rquote ll find that there is still one left in my shop. You see this little book?\'94 
\par \'93Well?\'94 
\par \'93That\rquote s the list of the folk from whom I buy. D\rquote you see? Well, then, here on this page are the country folk, and the numbe
rs after their names are where their accounts are in the big ledger. Now, then! You see this other page in red ink? Well, that is a list of my town suppliers. Now, look at that third name. Just read it out to me.\'94 
\par \'93Mrs. Oakshott, 117, Brixton Road\emdash 249,\'94 read Holmes. 
\par \'93Quite so. Now turn that up in the ledger.\'94 
\par Holmes turned to the page indicated. \'93Here you are, \lquote Mrs. Oakshott, 117, Brixton Road, egg and poultry supplier.\rquote \~\'94 
\par \'93Now, then, what\rquote s the last entry?\'94 
\par \'93\~\lquote December 22nd. Twenty-four geese at 7}{\i\insrsid3304115 s}{\insrsid3304115 . 6}{\i\insrsid3304115 d}{\insrsid3304115 .\rquote \~\'94 
\par \'93Quite so. There you are. And underneath?\'94 
\par \'93\~\lquote Sold to Mr. Windigate of the Alpha, at 12}{\i\insrsid3304115 s}{\insrsid3304115 .\rquote \~\'94 
\par \'93What have you to say now?\'94 
\par Sherlock Holmes looked deeply chagrined. He drew a sovereign from his pocket and threw it down upon the slab, turning away wi
th the air of a man whose disgust is too deep for words. A few yards off he stopped under a lamp-post and laughed in the hearty, noiseless fashion which was peculiar to him. 
\par \'93When you see a man with whiskers of that cut and the \lquote Pink \rquote un\rquote  protruding out of his pocket, you can always draw him by a bet,\'94 said he. \'93I daresay that if I had put }{\i\insrsid3304115 \'a3}{\insrsid3304115 
100 down in front of him, that man would not have given me such complete information as was drawn from him by the idea that he was doing me on a wager. Well, Watson, we
 are, I fancy, nearing the end of our quest, and the only point which remains to be determined is whether we should go on to this Mrs. Oakshott to-night, or whether we should reserve it for to-morrow. It is clear from what that surly fellow said that ther
e are others besides ourselves who are anxious about the matter, and I should\emdash \'94 
\par His remarks were suddenly cut short by a loud hubbub which broke out from the stall which we had just left. Turning round we saw a little rat-faced fellow standing in the centr
e of the circle of yellow light which was thrown by the swinging lamp, while Breckinridge, the salesman, framed in the door of his stall, was shaking his fists fiercely at the cringing figure. 
\par \'93I\rquote ve had enough of you and your geese,\'94 he shouted. \'93I wish you were all at the devil together. If you come pestering me any more with your silly talk I\rquote ll set the dog at you. You bring Mrs. Oakshott here and I\rquote 
ll answer her, but what have you to do with it? Did I buy the geese off you?\'94 
\par \'93No; but one of them was mine all the same,\'94 whined the little man. 
\par \'93Well, then, ask Mrs. Oakshott for it.\'94 
\par \'93She told me to ask you.\'94 
\par \'93Well, you can ask the King of Proosia, for all I care. I\rquote ve had enough of it. Get out of this!\'94 He rushed fiercely forward, and the inquirer flitted away into the darkness. 
\par \'93Ha! this may save us a visit to Brixton Road,\'94 whispered Holmes. \'93Come with me, and we will see what is to be made of this fellow.\'94 Striding through the scattered knots of people who lounged round the flaring stalls, my compan
ion speedily overtook the little man and touched him upon the shoulder. He sprang round, and I could see in the gas-light that every vestige of colour had been driven from his face. 
\par \'93Who are you, then? What do you want?\'94 he asked in a quavering voice. 
\par \'93You will excuse me,\'94 said Holmes blandly, \'93but I could not help overhearing the questions which you put to the salesman just now. I think that I could be of assistance to you.\'94 
\par \'93You? Who are you? How could you know anything of the matter?\'94 
\par \'93My name is Sherlock Holmes. It is my business to know what other people don\rquote t know.\'94 
\par \'93But you can know nothing of this?\'94 
\par \'93Excuse me, I know everything of it. You are endeavouring to trace some geese which were sold by Mrs. Oakshott, of Brixton Road, to a salesman name
d Breckinridge, by him in turn to Mr. Windigate, of the Alpha, and by him to his club, of which Mr. Henry Baker is a member.\'94 
\par \'93Oh, sir, you are the very man whom I have longed to meet,\'94 cried the little fellow with outstretched hands and quivering fingers. \'93I can hardly explain to you how interested I am in this matter.\'94 
\par Sherlock Holmes hailed a four-wheeler which was passing. \'93In that case we had better discuss it in a cosy room rather than in this wind-swept market-place,\'94 said he. \'93But pray tell me, be
fore we go farther, who it is that I have the pleasure of assisting.\'94 
\par The man hesitated for an instant. \'93My name is John Robinson,\'94 he answered with a sidelong glance. 
\par \'93No, no; the real name,\'94 said Holmes sweetly. \'93It is always awkward doing business with an alias.\'94 
\par A flush sprang to the white cheeks of the stranger. \'93Well then,\'94 said he, \'93my real name is James Ryder.\'94 
\par \'93Precisely so. Head attendant at the Hotel Cosmopolitan. Pray step into the cab, and I shall soon be able to tell you everything which you would wish to know.\'94 
\par The little man stood glancing from one to the other of us with half-frightened, half-hopeful eyes, as one who is not sure whether he is on the verge of a windfall or of a catastrophe. Then he stepped into the cab, and in half an ho
ur we were back in the sitting-room at Baker Street. Nothing had been said during our drive, but the high, thin breathing of our new companion, and the claspings and unclaspings of his hands, spoke of the nervous tension within him. 
\par \'93Here we are!\'94 said Holmes cheerily as we filed into the room. \'93
The fire looks very seasonable in this weather. You look cold, Mr. Ryder. Pray take the basket-chair. I will just put on my slippers before we settle this little matter of yours. Now, then! You want to know what became of those geese?\'94 
\par \'93Yes, sir.\'94 
\par \'93Or rather, I fancy, of that goose. It was one bird, I imagine in which you were interested\emdash white, with a black bar across the tail.\'94 
\par Ryder quivered with emotion. \'93Oh, sir,\'94 he cried, \'93can you tell me where it went to?\'94 
\par \'93It came here.\'94 
\par \'93Here?\'94 
\par \'93Yes, and a most remarkable bird it proved. I don\rquote t wonder that you should take an interest in it. It laid an egg after it was dead\emdash the bonniest, brightest little blue egg that ever was seen. I have it here in my museum.\'94 
\par Our v
isitor staggered to his feet and clutched the mantelpiece with his right hand. Holmes unlocked his strong-box and held up the blue carbuncle, which shone out like a star, with a cold, brilliant, many-pointed radiance. Ryder stood glaring with a drawn face
, uncertain whether to claim or to disown it. 
\par \'93The game\rquote s up, Ryder,\'94 said Holmes quietly. \'93Hold up, man, or you\rquote ll be into the fire! Give him an arm back into his chair, Watson. He\rquote s not got blood enough to go in for felony with impunity. Give him a dash 
of brandy. So! Now he looks a little more human. What a shrimp it is, to be sure!\'94 
\par For a moment he had staggered and nearly fallen, but the brandy brought a tinge of colour into his cheeks, and he sat staring with frightened eyes at his accuser. 
\par \'93I have 
almost every link in my hands, and all the proofs which I could possibly need, so there is little which you need tell me. Still, that little may as well be cleared up to make the case complete. You had heard, Ryder, of this blue stone of the Countess of M
orcar\rquote s?\'94 
\par \'93It was Catherine Cusack who told me of it,\'94 said he in a crackling voice. 
\par \'93I see\emdash her ladyship\rquote s waiting-maid. Well, the temptation of sudden wealth so easily acquired was too much for you, as it has been for better men before you; but you were 
not very scrupulous in the means you used. It seems to me, Ryder, that there is the making of a very pretty villain in you. You knew that this man Horner, the plumber, had been concerned in some such matter before, and that suspicion would rest the more r
eadily upon him. What did you do, then? You made some small job in my lady\rquote s room\emdash you and your confederate Cusack\emdash 
and you managed that he should be the man sent for. Then, when he had left, you rifled the jewel-case, raised the alarm, and had this unfortunate man arrested. You then\emdash \'94 
\par Ryder threw himself down suddenly upon the rug and clutched at my companion\rquote s knees. \'93For God\rquote s sake, have mercy!\'94 he shrieked. \'93Think of my father! Of my mother! It would break their hearts. I never went wrong before! I never 
will again. I swear it. I\rquote ll swear it on a Bible. Oh, don\rquote t bring it into court! For Christ\rquote s sake, don\rquote t!\'94 
\par \'93Get back into your chair!\'94 said Holmes sternly. \'93It is very well to cringe and crawl now, but you thought little enough of this poor Horner in the dock for a crime of which he knew nothing.\'94 
\par \'93I will fly, Mr. Holmes. I will leave the country, sir. Then the charge against him will break down.\'94 
\par \'93Hum! We will talk about that. And now let us hear a true account of the next act. How came the stone into the goose, and how came the goose into the open market? Tell us the truth, for there lies your only hope of safety.\'94 
\par Ryder passed his tongue over his parched lips. \'93I will tell you it just as it happened, sir,\'94 said he. \'93When Horner had been arrested, it 
seemed to me that it would be best for me to get away with the stone at once, for I did not know at what moment the police might not take it into their heads to search me and my room. There was no place about the hotel where it would be safe. I went out, 
as if on some commission, and I made for my sister\rquote 
s house. She had married a man named Oakshott, and lived in Brixton Road, where she fattened fowls for the market. All the way there every man I met seemed to me to be a policeman or a detective; and, for a
ll that it was a cold night, the sweat was pouring down my face before I came to the Brixton Road. My sister asked me what was the matter, and why I was so pale; but I told her that I had been upset by the jewel robbery at the hotel. Then I went into the 
back yard and smoked a pipe and wondered what it would be best to do. 
\par \'93I had a friend once called Maudsley, who went to the bad, and has just been serving his time in Pentonville. One day he had met me, and fell into talk about the ways of thieves, and how
 they could get rid of what they stole. I knew that he would be true to me, for I knew one or two things about him; so I made up my mind to go right on to Kilburn, where he lived, and take him into my confidence. He would show me how to turn the stone int
o
 money. But how to get to him in safety? I thought of the agonies I had gone through in coming from the hotel. I might at any moment be seized and searched, and there would be the stone in my waistcoat pocket. I was leaning against the wall at the time an
d looking at the geese which were waddling about round my feet, and suddenly an idea came into my head which showed me how I could beat the best detective that ever lived. 
\par \'93My sister had told me some weeks before that I might have the pick of her geese for
 a Christmas present, and I knew that she was always as good as her word. I would take my goose now, and in it I would carry my stone to Kilburn. There was a little shed in the yard, and behind this I drove one of the birds\emdash 
a fine big one, white, with a ba
rred tail. I caught it, and prying its bill open, I thrust the stone down its throat as far as my finger could reach. The bird gave a gulp, and I felt the stone pass along its gullet and down into its crop. But the creature flapped and struggled, and out 
came my sister to know what was the matter. As I turned to speak to her the brute broke loose and fluttered off among the others. 
\par \'93\~\lquote Whatever were you doing with that bird, Jem?\rquote  says she. 
\par \'93\~\lquote Well,\rquote  said I, \lquote you said you\rquote d give me one for Christmas, and I was feeling which was the fattest.\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote Oh,\rquote  says she, \lquote we\rquote ve set yours aside for you\emdash Jem\rquote s bird, we call it. It\rquote s the big white one over yonder. There\rquote 
s twenty-six of them, which makes one for you, and one for us, and two dozen for the market.\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote Thank you, Maggie,\rquote  says I; \lquote but if it is all the same to you, I\rquote d rather have that one I was handling just now.\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote The other is a good three pound heavier,\rquote  said she, \lquote and we fattened it expressly for you.\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote Never mind. I\rquote ll have the other, and I\rquote ll take it now,\rquote  said I. 
\par \'93\~\lquote Oh, just as you like,\rquote  said she, a little huffed. \lquote Which is it you want, then?\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote That white one with the barred tail, right in the middle of the flock.\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote Oh, very well. Kill it and take it with you.\rquote  
\par \'93Well, I did what she said, 
Mr. Holmes, and I carried the bird all the way to Kilburn. I told my pal what I had done, for he was a man that it was easy to tell a thing like that to. He laughed until he choked, and we got a knife and opened the goose. My heart turned to water, for th
ere was no sign of the stone, and I knew that some terrible mistake had occurred. I left the bird, rushed back to my sister\rquote s, and hurried into the back yard. There was not a bird to be seen there. 
\par \'93\~\lquote Where are they all, Maggie?\rquote  I cried. 
\par \'93\~\lquote Gone to the dealer\rquote s, Jem.\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote Which dealer\rquote s?\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote Breckinridge, of Covent Garden.\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote But was there another with a barred tail?\rquote  I asked, \lquote the same as the one I chose?\rquote  
\par \'93\~\lquote Yes, Jem; there were two barred-tailed ones, and I could never tell them apart.\rquote  
\par \'93Well, the
n, of course I saw it all, and I ran off as hard as my feet would carry me to this man Breckinridge; but he had sold the lot at once, and not one word would he tell me as to where they had gone. You heard him yourselves to-night. Well, he has always answe
red me like that. My sister thinks that I am going mad. Sometimes I think that I am myself. And now\emdash and now I am myself a branded thief, without ever having touched the wealth for which I sold my character. God help me! God help me!\'94
 He burst into convulsive sobbing, with his face buried in his hands. 
\par There was a long silence, broken only by his heavy breathing and by the measured tapping of Sherlock Holmes\rquote  finger-tips upon the edge of the table. Then my friend rose and threw open the door. 
\par \'93Get out!\'94 said he. 
\par \'93What, sir! Oh, Heaven bless you!\'94 
\par \'93No more words. Get out!\'94 
\par And no more words were needed. There was a rush, a clatter upon the stairs, the bang of a door, and the crisp rattle of running footfalls from the street. 
